If you want to ensure that the joke text within the `jokeContainer` is always red regardless of its original color (in case it's set elsewhere), you could slightly update the JavaScript code to replace the joke text with a `<span>` tag and apply the color directly:

### Updated JavaScript (script.js)

```javascript
document.getElementById('jokeButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
    const jokes = [
        "Why did the tomato turn red? Because it saw the salad dressing!",
        "I'm reading a book on anti-gravity. It's impossible to put down!",
        "I told my wife she was drawing her eyebrows too high. She looked surprised.",
        "Why don't skeletons fight each other? They don't have the guts."
    ];

    const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
    const joke = jokes[randomIndex];

    // Create a span element, display the joke, and apply the red color
    const jokeContainer = document.getElementById('jokeContainer');
    const jokeSpan = document.createElement('span');
    jokeSpan.style.color = 'red';
    jokeSpan.innerText = joke;
    jokeContainer.innerHTML = ''; // Clear any existing content
    jokeContainer.appendChild(jokeSpan);
});
```

This approach ensures that the color is applied directly to the text, making it red, no matter what it was before the joke was inserted.

